<p>"Indecent" redirects here. For the play, see <ref target="/wiki/Indecent_(play)" title="Indecent (play)">Indecent (play)</ref>.</p>



<p>Look up <ref class="extiw" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Special:Search/inappropriateness" title="wiktionary:Special:Search/inappropriateness">inappropriateness</ref> in Wiktionary, the free dictionary.</p>

<ref class="image" href="/wiki/File:Les_passions_humaines,_de_Jef_Lambeaux.jpg"></ref> <ref class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Les_passions_humaines,_de_Jef_Lambeaux.jpg" title="Enlarge"></ref>At the time, the <ref target='/wiki/Temple_of_Human_Passions#The_"Human_Passions"_relief' title="Temple of Human Passions">Human Passions relief</ref> by <ref target="/wiki/Jef_Lambeaux" title="Jef Lambeaux">Jef Lambeaux</ref> was deemed as indecent.
<p>Inappropriateness refers to standards or <ref target="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethics</ref> that are typically viewed as being negative in society.<ref target="#cite_note-1">[1]</ref> It differs from things that are illicit in that inappropriate behavior does not necessarily have any accompanying legal ramifications.<ref target="#cite_note-2">[2]</ref></p>

